### PDL
* Worked with Office of Science and Technology Policy (OSTP) last year for proto-content last year for Toolkit
    * Looking to augment with actionable skills training
    * Received 6 month grant from Schmidt Foundation to prototype
    * Working towards a business model and initial set of offerings to be self-sustaining
    * Possible to be a bootstrap but this would prove challenging
    * Taking a lean startup approach - ideating, validating, iterating
* Question for OPM: How have agencies approached OPM on HCD training?
* Building upon past research and relationships
* Adjacencies  - Create an adjacent space where you can create and have the flexibility to build what you need, and then when it's ready insert it back into the university (or public sector)
    * When building adjacencies you need to be very familiar with what&#39;s going on inside the organization
    * Ex: Kathleen deLaski - Education Design Lab
    * Looking to build something new of value and find the space to contribute where there&#39;s no current service offering

### INNOVATION AMBASSADOR'S NETWORK 
* Team of 3 working on Innovation Ambassadors Network
* Influencers -- Culture Change
    * Speakers Bureau - the Ambassadors Network is starting with this group; This can occur on multiple tiers/levels for example: leading a brown bag in a office kitchen vs. keynote speaker at a conference
    * In-house advocates - the subject matter expert (SME), internal consultant, Go-To person that has influence within the organizational context
    * Mentors - Focused on the  management level that will become innovation mentors to others
      * Question for OPM: Is there a speciality within the existing OPM mentorship programs that focuses in innovation?
* Enablers -- Develop Talent
    * Help other learn what they need to learn whether it is training, experiential, etc.
    * Trainers
    * Coaches
        * Fed-preneur = intrapreneurship or entrepreneurship within an organization
        * Coach training program is focused on finding existing coaches that want to be a Fed-preneur coach
    * Facilitators
        * Identify skilled facilitators throughout the government
        * Develop an apprentice program where talent is identified and given the skills/trainings to develop their talent
* Team Leads - Take Action
    * Crew Leaders
    * Question: How do Team Leads connect back to influencers?
    * There is an opportunity to leverage incoming GS-15 talent at the White House to experiment with these roles and how to implement them
    * Individuals do not have a specific budget or agenda; focused on enterprise leadership and not traditional management; program is one-year full-time
* This is a &quot;spreading program&quot;
* Question: Will there be a support group component of this program?
* Question: How will the Ambassador&#39;s Network integrate to the Better Government work?
* Community of Practice participants will be selected to participate in the Ambassador's program that will include various levels of badging
* Better Government is in the process of performing a "census" of innovators across the government
* Need to create a strawman before bringing to other leaders in government
* This design acknowledges differentiation between individuals - everyone has a role and can contribute to innovation
* In order to improve performance sustainability, we need to improve the execution of innovation

### CULINARY EXAMPLE FOR hUMAN PRODUCTIVE ACTIVITY 
* Cook (Manager) vs. Chef (Innovator)
* For any meal there are inputs, outputs, and a recipe
* However, a recipe doesn&#39;t include all of the aspects (environmental, cookware, etc.) of what will determine the outputs
* Chefs create new recipes - using new ingredients that are not nearby combinations
* The fundamentals in most industries are changing so rapidly and resources are constrained that organizations can't afford to have only "cooks" (manager)

## SHOULD WE SEPARATE OUT THE ROLE OF INNOVATOR VS.THE ROLE OF ENTREPRENEUR? 
* Innovation
    * Different ways to think about a given approach/product/service
    * If we're not clear about what we mean when we talk about innovation, then it means nothing
    * Better Government playbook approach:
        * Everyone can and should innovate -- but that doesn&#39;t mean everyone is leading innovation
        * We are trying to meet the question: can we turn the Federal government into the hub for innovation?
* Entrepreneurship
    * Entrepreneurs have to build the enterprise to deliver the innovation, being a disrupter is only one of the ten things an entrepreneur has to do
    * Pursuit of opportunity without resources currently controlled - Howard Stevenson
    * Entrepreneur is a residual claimant. It's not just profit, it's reputation and blame, and risk and exposure.
    * The entrepreneur is  accountable for both the upsides and downsides of their venture
    * NGDGU = "No good deed goes unpunished"
    * Fed-preneur = intrapreneur in a Federal context

### OPM
* Center for Leadership Development Organization Structure
    * Head of OPM is the President's advisor on Human Capital
    * Leader of Talent and Management to the government in a policy and service role
    * Unique position to lead a design movement through education
    * Driving leadership in government to be cross-sector
        * OPM has the authority to bring non-profit and corporate partners into our education
* Federal Education Institute
    * Executive Development Program
    * Presidential Management Fellows/Presidential Executive Fellows Program
    * The Lab
* Adopting university concept - inspired by NDU / Air University
 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

* Developing ECQ (Executive Core Qualifications) 27- 28 core competencies, one of which is innovation
* Certificate programs are bundled, which in the past have been  more opportunistic
* Investing in infrastructure for certificate of mastery
* Lab is fitting into the government career development path ( G7 - SES ) with the objective of driving leadership through design innovation
* Career-long curriculum divided into different disciplines designed to educate and transform people not just provide skills/techniques
* Enrique is helping build a combination of standalone design education programs and embedding design more fully into all of the CLP programs in order to build the leadership support for the intrapreneurs and remove barrier
* Drawing on a number of resources to build our curriculum:
    * Extensive research
    * Maturity model for designing government (not using I/O psychology methodologies)
    * Specific design traditions to understand what people need and what we can offer as they progress up the career leader and the continuum of leadership 
* Prototyping 3 offerings
* This was OPM's first experience in how to prototype new courses (e.g. what does it look like to roll them out)
* Question: Are there different types of managers based on talents/interests vs. one-size-fits-all?
* OPM doesn't understand the Federal leader as a single function or as a single role -- there are technical leads and transformational leads
* Anything CLD does is assessment based - when working with leaders we start with assessment so they can build on their strengths (MBTI, CCL, EQI)
    * George Mason Master&#39;s Program starts with a reflective retreat on life goals and direction

* Center for Leadership Development
    * Size/Location
        * 20,000 students  in classrooms - about a half come through OPM locations vs. other Federal buildings
        * 80,000 students online
        * Our size led to our realization that we are a "university"
    * Physical locations
        * Federal Executive Education - Charlottesville
        * Western Management Development - Denver
        * Eastern Management Development - Washington DC
   * Strategic pillars
         * Lead
         * Do - Project-based learning
         * What is happening in Agencies as they learn this and do within organization?
         * Feeds learning about maturity and feeds into curriculum; Feeds from deep conversations internal barriers and design projects
         * Teach = Workshop plus three course offerings (mapping, storytelling, and the "other one")

* Partnering with Chief Learning Officers
  * Working with CLOs to understand what makes sense for them to do internally VS. externally
  * Some Agencies opt to have their own university (i.e. VA, Interior, DOD)
  * We believe as a part of the shared service movement that there should be some coordination
  * Relationship with Tim O'Riley/Jen Pahlka
    * Over 15 years of experience in innovation in Government; book about Future of Work and Workforce issues
    * We are working at the intersection of Future of Work and Innovation in government

* In order to transform the work of the Federal government
    * Do we need buy in and vision and resources?
    * We need to create a vehicle that people can believe in
    * Private sector wants to know where the government is on Innovation and Entrepreneurship

### KEY ASSUMPTIONS 

* Cost affordable/accessible learning opportunities
* Need adjacencies AND internal/direct
 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

* Innovation = Practice
* Education = Training
* Education = Team over Individual
* People will self-identify as innovative/innov-curious
* Intrinsic rewards sufficient for ambassadors/other avenues for recognition
* Ambassador is an honor not &quot;not good deed goes unpunished&quot;
* We're finding Ambassadors who speak the language not perk-seekers
* Chief Influencer not Chief Listener
* In the Community of Practice -&gt; help Ambassador Program work
* Executive Core Qualifications are the right/best things to train/select leaders to
* Design is a cross-cutting dimension of Education for government leadership
* Partner Chief Learning Officers
* Lab@OPM Leader HC + Talent Management Policy + Service Role
* Design Movement through Innovation
* Cross Sector Partnership (Design Ed)
* Do we need buy-in and vision (at large)?
* We have all the right people in the room now (eg. if we build it they will come)
* Sufficient internal motivation external incentive for participants (for all modes of engagement)
* We are a venn structure vs. an adaptive network (a swarm)
* Bottom up and top down is the way to do this
* There is sufficient opportunity and willingness to make real change right now
* Most government workers _want_ to have capacity to innovate
* Most government workers _do not want_ to have capacity to innovate
